An Analysis on Public Safety in Vancouver

Background

In response to recent concerns regarding public safety in Vancouver, particularly in the downtown core, this report aims to provide an in-depth analysis of crime patterns over the past three years (September 2021 â August 2024). Our focus is on the most prevalent types of crimesâTheft from Vehicle, Mischief, and Offences Against a Personâwithin the neighbourhoods exhibiting the highest crime rates: Central Business District, West End, and Strathcona.

Crime Type Analysis

The selected crime typesâTheft from Vehicle, Mischief, and Offences Against a Personâstand out due to their prevalence and the public safety concerns they pose. Each category represents a unique challenge:

Theft from Vehicle:

Theft from Vehicle is a property crime that directly impacts both residents and visitors. The frequency of this crime type has been consistently high, as evidenced in the Columns plot visualization, which shows a significant concentration of incidents in the Central Business District and West End neighborhoods. The persistence of this crime can be linked to factors such as high vehicular congestion and insufficient parking security measures. Our analysis shows that peak instances of vehicle theft occur during weekends and holidays, which align with increased parking demands in commercial and tourist areasâ

Mischief:

Mischief-related offences, encompassing acts of vandalism and damage to property, have become increasingly common in areas like the West End. The smooth column plot reveals a steady upward trend in mischief cases, especially in residential and mixed-use zones, where economic disparities and community tensions can act as catalysts. This crime type not only results in direct financial loss but also diminishes the communityâs sense of security and belonging. Preventative strategies, such as neighborhood watch programs and community engagement initiatives, should be considered to curb this trendâ

Offences Against a Person:

Offences Against a Person include violent crimes such as assault and robbery. The column plot in our analysis indicates that these crimes are disproportionately concentrated in socio-economically disadvantaged neighborhoods like Strathcona. The frequency of such offences in Strathcona raises concerns about underlying social issues such as homelessness and substance abuse, which may contribute to heightened tensions and conflict. Addressing these issues will require an integrated approach that combines increased policing with enhanced social services and mental health supportâ

Neighborhood Analysis

The neighborhoods we have focused onâCentral Business District, West End, and Strathconaâare characterized by high crime rates relative to other areas in Vancouver. Each neighborhood presents distinct challenges that are reflected in the crime visualizations.

Central Business District:

The Central Business District, a hub of economic activity, has the highest frequency of Theft from Vehicle incidents, as shown in our scatter plot visualization. This can be attributed to the high concentration of parked vehicles and limited surveillance infrastructure in parking lots and public areas. Increasing police presence and deploying more CCTV cameras could serve as effective deterrents to reduce such crimesâ(

West End:

The West End, known for its residential character, has a notable spike in Mischief offences, as depicted in the smooth line plot. The increase in these crimes may be associated with seasonal fluctuations and increased community tensions. The implementation of community-based crime prevention programs, combined with improved street lighting and neighborhood patrols, would enhance safety and reduce mischief-related offencesâ.

Strathcona:

Strathconaâs proximity to the Downtown East-side makes it vulnerable to social challenges such as drug use and homelessness, which correlate with higher instances of Offences Against a Person, as shown in the density plot. This neighborhood requires a multifaceted approach that integrates law enforcement with social support services to address the root causes of these crimesâ.

Daily Incident Count for Top 3 Crime Types in Vancouverâs Most Dangerous Neighborhoods

This scatter plot visualizes the number of daily incidents for the top three crime typesâTheft from Vehicle, Mischief, and Offence Against a Personâwithin Vancouverâs Central Business District, West End, and Strathcona neighborhoods. The x-axis represents the date, and the y-axis displays the number of daily incidents.

The plot highlights fluctuations in crime trends over time, providing a clear visual representation of the frequency and intensity of these high-risk crimes from September 1, 2021, to August 31, 2024. This visual serves as a critical tool for understanding the temporal distribution of crime and evaluating potential policy interventions to enhance public safety in these vulnerable areas.

Trend Analysis of Daily Incidents for Top 3 Crime Types in Vancouverâs Most Dangerous Neighborhoods

This trend line plot provides a smoothed visualization of the daily incident count for the top three crime typesâTheft from Vehicle, Mischief, and Offence Against a Personâin Vancouverâs Central Business District, West End, and Strathcona neighborhoods. The x-axis shows the date, while the y-axis represents the number of daily incidents.

The smoothed line captures the overall trend of crime incidents from September 1, 2021, to August 31, 2024, highlighting significant patterns and changes in crime frequency over time. This analysis helps to identify periods of high activity and assess long-term shifts, offering an alternative way of viewing the same insights for formulating public safety strategies.

Crime Density Patterns in Vancouverâs High-Risk Neighborhoods

In response to the Mayorâs public safety concerns, this density plot illustrates the distribution of daily crime incidents for the three highest crime typesâTheft from Vehicle, Mischief, and Offence Against a Personâwithin Vancouverâs most dangerous neighborhoods: Central Business District, West End, and Strathcona.

The analysis spans the period from September 1, 2021, to August 31, 2024, providing a comprehensive view of crime trends over time. Each shaded area represents the frequency of daily incidents, with colors differentiating between the days of the week. The x-axis captures the count of daily incidents, capped at 60 for clarity, while the y-axis displays the density of these occurrences.

Conclusion and Recommendations:

Based on the findings from our crime and neighborhood analyses, it is evident that a targeted approach is necessary to enhance public safety in Vancouver. We recommend the following actions:

Strategic Allocation of Police Resources: Increase police patrols and surveillance measures in high-risk areas such as the Central Business District to deter vehicle theft and monitor potential criminal activity.

Community Engagement and Preventative Measures: Launch community engagement programs in the West End to foster a collaborative approach to crime prevention, focusing on mischief-related offences.

Integrated Social Support in Strathcona: Collaborate with local non-profit organizations and healthcare providers to deliver comprehensive social services in Strathcona, addressing homelessness, addiction, and mental health challenges that contribute to crime rates.

Crime Type Analysis Code Chunk

library(tidyverse)
library(ggthemes)
library(lubridate)
crime_data2024 <- read.csv("crimedata_csv_AllNeighbourhoods_2024.csv")
crime_data2023 <- read.csv("crimedata_csv_AllNeighbourhoods_2023.csv")
crime_data2022 <- read.csv("crimedata_csv_AllNeighbourhoods_2022.csv")
crime_data2021 <- read.csv("crimedata_csv_AllNeighbourhoods_2021.csv")
crime_data <- bind_rows(crime_data2024,crime_data2023,crime_data2022,crime_data2021)%>%
  mutate(date = make_date(YEAR,MONTH,DAY))
crime_data.5 <- filter(crime_data,date >= "2021-09-01" & date <= "2024-08-31")

crime_data1 <- group_by(crime_data.5, TYPE)

crime_data2 <- filter(crime_data1, TYPE!="Other Theft")

crime_data3 <-summarise(crime_data2,
                         count_TYPE = n())
ggplot(data = crime_data3, mapping = aes(x = reorder(TYPE,count_TYPE), y= count_TYPE))+labs(x= "Type of Crime", y= "Occurance of the Crime in the last 4 Years", title = "Determining the most prevalent crime in Vancouver Neighbourhoods") + geom_col() +theme_economist() + coord_flip()

Neighborhood Analysis Code Chunk

ncrime_data1 <- group_by(crime_data.5, NEIGHBOURHOOD) %>% 
  summarise(count = n())

ggplot(ncrime_data1, mapping = aes(x=reorder(NEIGHBOURHOOD, -count), y=count)) +geom_col() +labs(x="Vancouver Neighbourhood", y="Number of Crimes") + theme_economist() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust=1))

Daily Incident Count for Top 3 Crime Types in Vancouverâs Most Dangerous Neighborhoods Code Chunk

highest_3_types1<-crime_data.5%>%
  filter(TYPE=="Theft from Vehicle"|TYPE=="Mischief"|TYPE=="Offence Against a Person")%>%
  mutate(date=make_date(YEAR,MONTH,DAY))%>%
  filter(date>="2021-09-01"&date<="2024-08-31")%>%
  filter(NEIGHBOURHOOD=="Central Business District"|NEIGHBOURHOOD=="West End"|NEIGHBOURHOOD=="Strathcona")%>%
  group_by(date)%>%
  summarize(daily_highest_3_crime_types1=n())

highest_3_types1%>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x=date,y=daily_highest_3_crime_types1)) + 
  geom_point()+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 11))+
  labs(x="Date",y="Number of Crime",
       title = "Daily 3 Highest Crime Types of 3 Most Dangerous Neighbourhoods in Vancouver") +theme_economist()

Crime Density Patterns in Vancouverâs High-Risk Neighborhoods Code Chunk

highest_3_types1%>% mutate(day_of_week=wday(date, label=TRUE)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x=daily_highest_3_crime_types1, fill=day_of_week, color=day_of_week)) + 
  geom_density(alpha=0.2) + 
  coord_cartesian(xlim=c(0,60)) +
  theme_economist() + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 11),
        axis.title.x = element_text(size = 10),
        legend.position = "right")+
  labs(x="Daily 3 Highest Crime types in Vancouver 3 Most Dangerous Neighbourhoods",
       title = "3 Highest Crime types in Vancouver 3 Most Dangerous Neighbourhoods",
       fill="Day of the week", 
       color="Day of the week")
